The pre-Chalk rustc trait solver accumulated several long-standing soundness issues, especially around higher-ranked trait bounds, lifetime inference inside trait obligations, and projection cycles. The next-generation solver — derived from Chalk's design but written natively in rustc — was conceived to:

- replace the legacy trait selector wholesale with a single canonical implementation;
- close known soundness bugs that the legacy solver could not fix without breaking compilation;
- improve compile times on trait-heavy crates by avoiding redundant solver invocations;
- give future trait-system features (specialization, generic associated types, async traits) a cleaner foundation.

For language designers building trait-like systems from scratch, the lesson is that **trait-solver architecture is foundational**: a solver that grows organically around features tends to accumulate soundness debt; a solver designed up front around an extensible logic-programming abstraction stays maintainable across feature additions.
